 It has a really boring name.

1795
00:46:43,580 --> 00:46:44,940
 It's called Asset Locks.

1796
00:46:44,940 --> 00:46:46,420
 Forget that I said that.

1797
00:46:47,080 --> 00:46:50,460
 Actually, what it is, is you can combine all these different tools.

1798
00:46:50,460 --> 00:46:53,860
 You can use things like foundation-owned companies.

1799
00:46:53,860 --> 00:47:01,120
 You can also add these other things called golden shares, which are basically like a single share with veto votes.

1800
00:47:01,120 --> 00:47:08,620
 And the veto can basically prevent the directors from doing certain things with companies, like selling them.

1801
00:47:09,620 --> 00:47:14,500
 Or also, changing the mission in the statutes, and these kinds of things.

1802
00:47:14,500 --> 00:47:20,240
 And the term that we typically use for all of this is called steward ownership.

1803
00:47:20,240 --> 00:47:24,000
 Now, there's different variants of steward ownership.

1804
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:28,920
 There's variants with stronger asset locks, and there's also versions with weaker asset locks.

1805
00:47:28,920 --> 00:47:32,240
 And the weaker asset locks are for people who think that they need investment.

1806
00:47:32,620 --> 00:47:37,960
 So, but I'm actually most interested in the versions with stronger asset locks.

1807
00:47:37,960 --> 00:47:49,100
 And the reason why I care so much about asset locks is because locking the value inside the company is really what you need to be able to thoroughly realign those incentives.

1808
00:47:49,100 --> 00:47:59,760
 And I mentioned earlier that, you know, I'm doing this to try and take a systems thinking approach to business.

1809
00:48:00,480 --> 00:48:04,800
 Now, systems thinking is actually a very interesting topic.

1810
00:48:04,800 --> 00:48:10,800
 And, well, the mother of systems thinking is Danella Meadows.

1811
00:48:10,800 --> 00:48:14,180
 She wrote a really wonderful book called Thinking in Systems.

1812
00:48:14,180 --> 00:48:22,460
 And it turns out that she was also one of the initial authors on the Limits to Growth report.

1813
00:48:22,460 --> 00:48:28,620
 That was a joint collaboration between MIT and the Club of Rome a little over 50 years ago.

1814
00:48:28,760 --> 00:48:35,460
 And they were actually one of the, it was a computer simulation that actually looked to see our growth trajectories.

1815
00:48:35,460 --> 00:48:41,320
 And they basically said, you know, they put us on the so-called business as usual path.

1816
00:48:41,320 --> 00:48:47,340
 And basically said, you know, we need to get on a different path or we're going to start using up our natural resources.

1817
00:48:48,380 --> 00:48:53,240
 So, it turns out for the 50th anniversary, they did an update of this report.

1818
00:48:53,240 --> 00:48:56,280
 And it turns out we're still on the business as usual path.

1819
00:48:56,280 --> 00:49:05,980
 So, but anyhow, but the point though with systems thinking is that systems thinking is a way of trying to fix problems.

1820
00:49:06,780 --> 00:49:10,680
 So, let's say that I go for a walk in the park.

1821
00:49:10,680 --> 00:49:14,000
 And I'm walking through the park near my house.

1822
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:16,740
 And then I see that there's a piece of garbage on the ground.

1823
00:49:16,740 --> 00:49:19,540
 So, I pick, I bend over.

1824
00:49:19,540 --> 00:49:20,980
 I pick up the piece of trash.

1825
00:49:20,980 --> 00:49:22,220
 And I want to throw it out.

1826
00:49:22,220 --> 00:49:25,160
 And then I notice that, hey, there's no garbage bins.

1827
00:49:26,340 --> 00:49:28,840
 So, then I say, okay, well, that's the problem.

1828
00:49:28,840 --> 00:49:32,860
 You know, and then I go and I petition the city because we need garbage bins in the park.

1829
00:49:32,860 --> 00:49:33,920
 All right, fine.

1830
00:49:33,920 --> 00:49:35,360
 So, I petition the city.

1831
00:49:35,360 --> 00:49:37,020
 Now, I've got the garbage bin.

1832
00:49:37,020 --> 00:49:40,920
 I come back a month later and I see another piece of trash on the ground.

1833
00:49:40,920 --> 00:49:43,360
 And I think, okay, I pick it up.

1834
00:49:43,360 --> 00:49:45,260
 I walk to the garbage bin.

1835
00:49:45,260 --> 00:49:47,140
 And it's overflowing.

1836
00:49:47,140 --> 00:49:50,500
 And then I think, hmm, that didn't solve the problem.

1837
00:49:50,500 --> 00:49:55,680
 So, then instead what I do, it's like peeling back the layers of the onion.

1838
00:49:56,340 --> 00:50:01,920
 You know, that I then think, well, where is all of this, where are all of these, where

1839
00:50:01,920 --> 00:50:04,960
 is all of the packaging coming from in the first place, right?

1840
00:50:04,960 --> 00:50:07,640
 And then I start looking at the manufacturing supply chain.

1841
00:50:07,640 --> 00:50:10,980
 Now, this is systems thinking.

1842
00:50:10,980 --> 00:50:17,800
 Because oftentimes, it's very attractive for us when we want to solve problems, particularly

1843
00:50:17,800 --> 00:50:24,020
 environmental and social problems, that we go after the symptoms, right?

1844
00:50:24,760 --> 00:50:29,680
 But the problem, though, is what we actually need to do is peel back that onion and try

1845
00:50:29,680 --> 00:50:31,760
 looking for the root cause.

1846
00:50:31,760 --> 00:50:33,180
 You know?

1847
00:50:33,180 --> 00:50:40,220
 And it's kind of like in the trilogy of ESG, environmental, social, and governance.

1848
00:50:40,220 --> 00:50:44,840
 You know, the E for environment is very popular.

1849
00:50:45,340 --> 00:50:49,760
 I mean, in part because people have climate anxiety, you know?

1850
00:50:49,760 --> 00:50:54,900
 Also because things like carbon emissions, they're kind of easy to measure.

1851
00:50:54,900 --> 00:50:56,600
 We sort of understand it.

1852
00:50:56,600 --> 00:50:58,200
 It's tangible, right?

1853
00:50:58,200 --> 00:50:59,140
 So, the E is popular.

1854
00:50:59,140 --> 00:51:02,800
 The S for society, it's a bit more fuzzy.

1855
00:51:02,800 --> 00:51:06,900
 It's still popular because, well, we don't like economic inequality.

1856
00:51:07,280 --> 00:51:10,920
 But, like, how do you measure things like racism or, you know?

1857
00:51:10,920 --> 00:51:15,960
 I mean, it's harder to measure, you know, but it's still sort of popular.

1858
00:51:15,960 --> 00:51:20,560
 Now, the G for governance is the orphan child.

1859
00:51:21,220 --> 00:51:23,220
 It is the dust swept under the rug.

1860
00:51:23,220 --> 00:51:28,500
 But the problem, though, is that the E and the S are symptoms.

1861
00:51:28,500 --> 00:51:31,580
 And the G is the root cause.

1862
00:51:33,160 --> 00:51:36,640
 In Dutch, we have a beautiful phrase for this.

1863
00:51:36,640 --> 00:51:39,820
 In Dutch, it's called dvijl met de kran open.

1864
00:51:39,820 --> 00:51:45,220
 In English, that translates to mopping with the faucet open.

1865
00:51:45,220 --> 00:51:52,340
 So, what winds up happening is we are sitting here mopping the environmental and social problems

1866
00:51:52,340 --> 00:51:56,220
 while it turns out that governance is the faucet.

1867
00:51:56,220 --> 00:52:00,980
 And what we actually need to do is we need to turn off that darn faucet.

1868
00:52:02,820 --> 00:52:10,820
 So, you know, but the problem, though, is that the G is very unpopular in a capacity

1869
00:52:10,820 --> 00:52:17,480
 because the E and the S, particularly the E, are much easier to greenwash with.

1870
00:52:17,480 --> 00:52:23,580
 And the G, I mean, the best we can seem to do with the G is, you know,

1871
00:52:23,580 --> 00:52:26,680
 G, I think I'll put more women on the board.

1872
00:52:26,680 --> 00:52:30,720
 And, I mean, look, nothing against board diversity, right?

1873
00:52:30,720 --> 00:52:34,520
 I mean, sure, of course we need more women on the board and other minorities,

1874
00:52:34,520 --> 00:52:37,480
 but it needs to not end there.

1875
00:52:37,480 --> 00:52:44,620
 We need to look at financial extraction, you know, things like, you know,

1876
00:52:44,620 --> 00:52:49,140
 the board, you know, the compensation for executives and board members, you know,

1877
00:52:49,140 --> 00:52:53,540
 and merger and acquisition activity and all kinds of other ways of extracting value from the company.

1878
00:52:53,540 --> 00:52:57,260
 That's actually the G that is really influencing things.

1879
00:52:57,260 --> 00:53:01,800
 But very few people, you know, pay attention to this.

1880
00:53:01,800 --> 00:53:12,340
 So, and this is also in part why a very large outcry against ESG investment has risen up in the United States.

1881
00:53:12,340 --> 00:53:20,240
 You know, to a large part because of all kinds of claims of greenwashing, which, to be quite frank, are true.

1882
00:53:20,240 --> 00:53:28,000
 And in that sense, it is sort of an open secret within the investment and finance industry about the greenwashing.

1883
00:53:28,860 --> 00:53:34,860
 The sustainable fund managers, of course they know it's there, you know, and they'll talk about it amongst themselves.

1884
00:53:34,860 --> 00:53:37,620
 I mean, they certainly can't put it in the marketing literature.

1885
00:53:37,620 --> 00:53:40,880
 And some of them, though, they are good people.

1886
00:53:40,880 --> 00:53:47,400
 They go into ESG investing precisely because they want to build something better, you know,

1887
00:53:47,400 --> 00:53:51,940
 because they don't want to be in the commercial finance industry because it's too toxic.

1888
00:53:53,140 --> 00:53:55,840
 But the problem is they don't know how to fix it.

1889
00:53:55,840 --> 00:54:06,860
 Now, the way that you can fix sustainable finance is, again, coming back to the same thing, eliminate the financial extraction.

1890
00:54:06,860 --> 00:54:09,540
 And how exactly would you do this?

1891
00:54:09,540 --> 00:54:12,360
 What does financial extraction look like in the finance industry?

1892
00:54:12,360 --> 00:54:18,280
 Well, first of all, you can use, again, steward ownership kinds of constructions in finance.

1893
00:54:18,280 --> 00:54:21,560
 You can use foundation ownership and golden shares.

1894
00:54:21,900 --> 00:54:27,820
 And the other thing with investment funds is fees are the way that cash leak out of investment funds.

1895
00:54:27,820 --> 00:54:36,160
 So you can basically take, there's something typically called the 220, 2% asset under management fee, 20% carried interest.

1896
00:54:36,160 --> 00:54:38,560
 And I can explain to you what these things mean.

1897
00:54:38,560 --> 00:54:41,380
 So carried interest.

1898
00:54:41,380 --> 00:54:43,640
 Let's say I'm a venture capitalist.

1899
00:54:43,640 --> 00:54:49,000
 And let's say that you are the founder of my portfolio company, right?

1900
00:54:49,420 --> 00:54:59,540
 So what happens is if you, your startup grows exponentially and then exits, with 20% carried interest, I get 20% of that.

1901
00:54:59,540 --> 00:55:09,760
 And that is a super powerful motivator for me, as a venture capitalist, to push you to grow exponentially and exits, right?

1902
00:55:10,300 --> 00:55:15,900
 So what you can say is that carried interest embeds the growth imperative into startups.

1903
00:55:15,900 --> 00:55:33,920
 So if instead you want to build companies that are oriented towards the long term, that can grow organically, you know, and are oriented for impact, then all, it really is as simple as eliminating that 20% carry.

1904
00:55:34,920 --> 00:55:38,160
 Same thing with the 2% asset under management fee.

1905
00:55:38,160 --> 00:55:45,120
 That's also very extractive, not if you're a small fund manager, but definitely if you're BlackRock or one of the big asset managers.

1906
00:55:45,120 --> 00:55:51,960
 And that can also be reformed to the cost of running the business, assuming middle class salaries and a pension.

1907
00:55:51,960 --> 00:56:02,000
 And there are fund managers already that are doing this, like Snowball Impact Management in the UK and Purpose Ventures in Germany.

1908
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:21,360
 So, in other words, what we need to do is we need to reform business and reform the finance industry so we can basically keep the aspects of human organization in a financially self-sustaining way,

1909
00:56:21,360 --> 00:56:28,920
 but at the same time to be able to pull out that financial extraction because it does not need to be there.

1910
00:56:30,180 --> 00:56:37,860
 Anyhow, I think that we're getting close to time where I'm going to need to wrap this up.

1911
00:56:37,860 --> 00:56:51,840
 So I would like to just leave you with a few last thoughts, one of which is after four or five years of running Radically Open Security, you know, and also making all these donations,

1912
00:56:52,840 --> 00:56:57,500
 founders started coming up to me and saying, hey, Melanie, great company you've got there.

1913
00:56:57,500 --> 00:56:59,180
 Can you help me to build something similar?

1914
00:56:59,180 --> 00:57:11,680
 So that was when I started Nonprofit Ventures, which is a startup incubator for, well, basically focused on nonprofit entity forums,

1915
00:57:11,680 --> 00:57:15,360
 steward ownership, and cross-ubsidizing charity with your profits.

1916
00:57:15,700 --> 00:57:20,980
 You would think, well, how many founders are as crazy as me, you know, to want to do this kind of thing?

1917
00:57:20,980 --> 00:57:22,720
 Turns out, quite a lot.

1918
00:57:22,720 --> 00:57:26,200
 We've run four cohorts through the program.

1919
00:57:26,200 --> 00:57:28,320
 We've incubated almost 60 startups.

1920
00:57:28,980 --> 00:57:33,420
 And in fact, this upcoming week, we're right about to open our call for applications for the fifth cohort.

1921
00:57:33,420 --> 00:57:35,160
 So if any of you are interested.

1922
00:57:35,160 --> 00:57:49,100
 The second thing also is I took the material from the incubator, generalized it a bit, and created a class at the University of Amsterdam Business School called Post-Growth Entrepreneurship.

1923
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:55,780
 This class, I've already taught it for the second year to 120 third-year bachelor students.

1924
00:57:55,780 --> 00:57:59,280
 It's part of the economics and sustainability minor.

1925
00:57:59,280 --> 00:58:05,760
 So, and it turns out, actually, a second business school has already adopted the course.

1926
00:58:05,760 --> 00:58:15,440
 The Autonomous University of Barcelona also enlisted my help with teaching a degrowth entrepreneurship two-course module as well.

1927
00:58:15,840 --> 00:58:18,980
 So, which business school is next?

1928
00:58:18,980 --> 00:58:20,140
 Maybe University of Split?

1929
00:58:20,140 --> 00:58:31,020
 But, but look, but the point here is that, you know, it all starts with having the discussion.

1930
00:58:31,020 --> 00:58:33,360
 It starts with the discourse.

1931
00:58:33,360 --> 00:58:39,260
 Because it turns out that there is tools that we can use that most people don't even know exist.

1932
00:58:39,260 --> 00:58:43,080
 And these days, it's super easy to be angry.

1933
00:58:43,720 --> 00:58:49,860
 It's super easy, you know, to blame other people, to hate each other, to get polarized, to get divisive.

1934
00:58:49,860 --> 00:58:53,000
 It's far more productive to build things.

1935
00:58:53,000 --> 00:59:02,000
 Yet people can't make the decision to embrace and use these new tools until they first know that they exist.

1936
00:59:03,360 --> 00:59:08,680
 So, what I can say is, first of all, educate yourself.

1937
00:59:08,680 --> 00:59:13,800
 If you are interested in learning more, of course, a one-hour lecture is very short.

1938
00:59:13,800 --> 00:59:19,860
 But I also recorded my post-growth entrepreneurship class at the University of Amsterdam.

1939
00:59:19,860 --> 00:59:24,480
 I hired in a professional film crew and gave the videos to a professional editor.

1940
00:59:24,860 --> 00:59:31,000
 And I put the videos online on YouTube for free with a Creative Commons license.

1941
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:39,180
 So, I would say anyone who is interested in seeing these videos, you can go to the YouTube channel of Nonprofit Ventures.

1942
00:59:39,180 --> 00:59:42,660
 I would also encourage you to connect with me on LinkedIn.

1943
00:59:42,660 --> 00:59:44,200
 My name is Melanie Ryback.

1944
00:59:45,060 --> 00:59:53,180
 And you can also, it's pinned to the top of my LinkedIn feed, but also I'm constantly putting out new videos, new content.

1945
00:59:53,180 --> 00:59:55,820
 All of it is open source and available for free.

1946
00:59:55,820 --> 01:00:02,680
 So, with that, if anyone has any questions, I would certainly be happy to take them.

1947
01:00:02,680 --> 01:00:05,380
 And for the rest, I appreciate your time and attention.

1948
01:00:05,540 --> 01:00:06,160
 Thank you so much.

